spotify: Reuse artist, album, and track modelsThis adds a module-level cache of artist, album, and track models, whosencontent is almost entirely static. This cache is used when we convert fromnpyspotify to Mopidy objects.nnPreviously, an album with 15 tracks would create 15 track objects, 15 artistsnobjects on the tracks, 15 album objects on the tracks, and 15 artist objects onnthe 15 album objects, in total 60 objects. With this change, we only create 15ntrack objects, 1 album object, and 1 artist object, in total 17 objects.nnMeasurements with 90 playlists containing about 6500 tracks in total shows thatnthis reduces the number of Artist objects from 13600 to 3800, and the number ofnAlbum objects from 6500 to 4500 objects.nnAn unscientific measurement of memory usage using ps(1) indicated a reductionnin RSS from 71MB to 65MB, measured right after the Spotify playlists was loadednthe first time.n

Detangle EOT and EOS.This commit tries to detangle EOS from EOT which we have incorrectlynintermingled. EOS events should only be happening at the end of the playlistnwhen we are about to stop. EOT handling has been removed / broken in thisnchange, and will need to be re-added with proper tests.n

Add change track to playback providers.This method is intended to make implementing EOT handling much more streamlinednby adding a way to easily just change the URI and any other state withoutnmessing with gstreamer pipe statesnnNaming of this is a bit unfortunate as it is not the same as thencore.playback's concept of change_track. At least not yetn

Use source's factory name to determine type.Checking the URI inside the new-source handler turned out to tickle some issuenthat gave us deadlocks. Getting the source and checking which factory creatednit is much safer.n

Setup about to finish handling for proper EOT support.With this change we ask the core.playback system to set the next tracks uri andnotherwise update state as needed. With this change we should be able to supportnstreaming oggs and gapless playback to mention a few of items this fixes.nnOn the down side, this change breaks test_end_of_track_skips_to_next_track_on_failurenas there is no clean way to handle this with the async nature of this EOTnhandling.n

Fix use of threading.Event for Python 2.6 and clear connected state.threading.Event's wait method returns None on python pre 2.7, which means allnsearches would fail. This also corrects that fact that we weren't clearing thenconnected threading event on disconnects. I did not add any tests for this atnthis time as I just want to get the fix out.n

Add caveat about static in sound test file.Add a note saying that the purpose of the aplay ... Front_Center.wav line is merely to test whether the sound works or not, rather than to test its quality.rnrnAnecdotally, I had very static-y sound from the aplay command, which prompted me to incorrectly believe that my sound would not work with Mopidy. As it turns out, the sound works fine using Mopidy or gstreamer. This note will hopefully keep other Mopidy users from thinking their sound is broken when it is not. (I ended up installing armhf version and trying to use despotify, which didn't work, before coming back to Mopidy.)

config: Add keyring module with fetch and set.New config submodule for fetching secrets from a secrets service over dbus. Tonfacilitate this we add a section and key to the stored attributes, allowing usnto fetch all mopidy values from the keyring and map them to the correct confignvalues.nnA helper for setting values is also added. Due to differences in in the secretsndbus API across versions of the APIs and various states of support in thensecrets service we try and open the default, login and finally sessionnkeyrings for storage.nnLocked keyrings will be dismissed for all operations.n

audio: Start adding playlist typefinder code.This allows gstreamer pipelines to determine when they are getting m3u, pls ornxspf files and distinguish them from text/plain content.n
audio: Add simple parsers for m3u, pls, xspf and uri lists.These parsers, and the detectors should probably be moved out at some point,nbut for now the simple version of these will do.n
audui: Add BasePlaylistElementThis element is the building block for the decoders that will convertnthe m3u, pls and xspf files to urilists and also the urilist player.n
audio: Add playlist decoders.These elements convert their respective formats to an urilist that we cannhandle in a genric way.n

audio: A uri list element.This element simply takes the list of uris that our other elements havenalready converted to simpler format, picks the first uri and play it. Thisnis done by ensuring that we block the right EOS messages, and all new segmentnmessages from the original sources. With these events blocked we can injectnour own nested uridecodebin to play the uri and push our own data. The nestednuridecodebin is setup with caps('any') to ensure that we don't suddenly demuxnand end up with multiple streams by accident.n
audio: Cleanup playlists elements docs and interace.
audio: Add IcySrc.Quick hack that wraps a regular HTTP src in a custom bin that converts icy://nto http:// - this is needed to get for instance http://somafm.com/m3u/groovesalad.m3unto work.n

audio: Re-add improved version of python based scanner.- Unlike the old python version we do not wait for the first audio handoff, wen  only progress until the PAUSED state. This ensure we don't block on empty files.n- Instead of using the signal watch and running the main loop we simply polln  the messages from the bus directly allowing for a synchronous code flow.n- Between each file the pipeline is always returned to NULL, this is done as wen  found that gst 0.10 will slow down as the uribin does not cleanup then  children it creates for handling each file. This issue is not present in 1.0.n- This also works around a segfault that was likely caused by a race conditionn  that seems to trigger in the 0.10 version of the pbutils discoverer.n- This version of the scanner also fixes the per track slow down, and works outn  to be considerably faster than even the built in discoverer from 1.0.n- Finally this removes the WMA hack as I kan no longer find any evidence of itn  being needed.n

Preliminary commit for browserify compatibilityThis is the first stage of my commits for issue #609 that will make thennpm module browserify friendly and browser friendly.nnThe grunt-browserify module has been introduced to replacengrunt-contrib-concat. Browserify automatically concatenates files and sonthere is no need for a concat step.nnThe faye-websocket module was problematic so I moved the require out tona separate module within the lib directory. The websocket module is anfolder containing a package.json, directing library consumers to thenentry point that is appropriate for their environment. Browserify picksnbrowser.js (which simply returns an object holding window.WebSocket)nwhile everyone else gets the faye-websocket module.nnIn addition, as browserify handles all the requires, there's no need tondetect the environment or include any pre-built modules. I've removednthe pre-built when and faye-websocket files in favour of lettingnbrowserify use the modules within node_modules. This should make itneasier to maintain dependencies in future versions of this library.nnOne side effect of this browserify compatibility is that, in order tonallow the library to be globally available in the browser as `Mopidy`,nI've had to set Mopidy as the exported object instead of as a key of thenexported object. To elaborate further, the current API would be like thenfollowing:nnvar Mopidy = require('mopidy').Mopidy;nnHowever, with this change, the API would be like this:nnvar Mopidy = require('mopidy');nnI'm not sure whether this would be an issue and so I think it's worthndiscussing further. It's possible that node developers won't have anproblem but, if they did, a potential workaround within the mopidy.jsnfile would be:nn   Mopidy.Mopidy = Mopidy;nnThis would allow developers to choose either of the following:nnvar Mopidy = require('mopidy');nvar Mopidy = require('mopidy').Mopidy;nnCould be a little odd to do this thoughnnWhen testing the browserify build, I noticed a strange error thrown whennmaking the initial websocket connection. I managed to track it down tonan IE 'feature' that crops up when you alias in-built functions. Innparticular, the when module was aliasing setImmediate to an internalnfunction (nextTick.) In a newer version of when, the function isninstead aliased to the browserify process.nextTick. This works wellnbecause substack already had that covered.nnWith when@2.7.0, IE11 appears to be working well. IE10 is still pendingna test.n

core: Make events emitted on playback consistent (fixes #629)This commit does not try to make the events correct/perfect with regard tonGStreamer states, end-of-stream signalling, etc. It only tries to make thenevents work consistently across all the methods on the playback controller.nn* play(track) while already playing has changed from:nn  - playback_state_changed(old_state='playing', new_state='playing')n  - track_playback_started(track=...)nn  to:nn  - playback_state_changed(old_state='playing', new_state='stopped')n  - track_playback_ended(track=..., time_position=...)n  - playback_state_changed(old_state='stopped', new_state='playing')n  - track_playback_started(track=...)nn* next() has changed from:nn  - track_playback_ended(track=..., time_position=...)n  - playback_state_changed(old_state='playing', new_state='stopped')n  - track_playback_ended(track=..., time_position=0)n  - playback_state_changed(old_state='stopped', new_state='playing')n  - track_playback_started(track=...)nn  to same as play() above.nn* previous() has changed in the same way as next().nn* on_end_of_track() has changed from:nn  - track_playback_ended(track=..., time_position=...)n  - playback_state_changed(old_state='playing', new_state='playing')n  - track_playback_started(track=...)nn  to same as play() above.nn* stop() has reordered its events from:nn  - track_playback_ended(track=..., time_position=...)n  - playback_state_changed(old_state='playing', new_state='stopped')nn  to:nn  - playback_state_changed(old_state='playing', new_state='stopped')n  - track_playback_ended(track=..., time_position=...)n

mpd: Write commands helper for tokenized command handlingThis provides a class which works as a command registry. Functions are added tonthe registry through a method on the class `add`.  Add acts as a decoratorntaking in the name of the command and optionally type converters for arguments.nnWhen handling requests, we can now tokenize the line, and then just pass thenarguments to our commands helper. It will lookup the correct handler and applynany validation before calling the original function.nnFor the sake of testing the original function is not wrapped. This thenfunctions, and anything testing them directly can simply assume pre-convertedndata as long as type annotations are in place.nnA sample usage would be:nn@protocol.commands.add('addid', position=protocol.integer)ndef addid(context, uri, position=None)npassnndef handle_request(line):ntokens = protocol.tokenizer(line)ncontext = ...nresult = protocol.commands.call(tokens, context=context)n

Pause gstreamer when bufferingWhen the `playbin2` pipeline is in `PLAYING` state and its buffer is empty thenpipeline will consume arriving data immediately. If the source is an HTTPnstream this leads to choppy playback. To fix this we pause playing when thenbuffer is nearly empty and wait for it to fill up until we resume playing. Thisnapproach is recommended in the gstreamer manual [1].nnWe might want to extract the hard-coded 10% mark and make it configurable.nn[1]: http://gstreamer.freedesktop.org/data/doc/gstreamer/head/manual/html/chapter-buffering.htmln

Set buffer properties of gstreamer pipelineManually set the `playbin2` buffer properties to their default values. Thendefault values are not documented but hard-coded in gstreamer [1].nnThis is a starting point for making these properties configurable. For examplenwe might want higher values on system with unsteady network connection.nn[1]: http://cgit.freedesktop.org/gstreamer/gst-plugins-base/tree/gst/playback/gsturidecodebin.c?h=0.10#n1714n

Donu00e2u0080u0099t start playing automatically when buffer is fullPreviously, when `Audio.pause_playback()` was called while buffering, the audionactor would switch back to the playing state when the buffer was full.n

zeroconf: Fix intermittent dbus/avahi exceptionThis fixes an issue where I sometimes would get an error from dbusn'Unable to guess signature from an empty list'. After some diggingnand checking the avahi dbus specs I found they expect the text listnto have a signature of 'aay' (an array of arrays containing bytes).nSo instead of using python lists we now use a 'typed' dbus array.nnIt is not clear to me why this is a heisenbug, but this fix doesnseem to make it go away.n

main: Ensure that exit_status_code always is assignedKeyboardInterrupts are not always catched in commands.py. As far as Inhave seen, if I/O operations are ongoing, a KeyboardInterrupt may benraised there instead of in commands.py. In some cases, this may causenloop.run() to return, which previously resulted in exit_status_codenbeing referenced before assignment.n

network: disable_recv before telling actor to close connectionAs of d62ad96, when the connection can't receive more data from thenclient, it tells the actor to stop the connection and callsndisable_recv(). The actor operates in it's own thread and when it stopsnthe connection, disable_recv is being called again from a differentnthread. Since the actor is told to stop the connection beforendisable_recv is called, the two calls to disable_recv may happennsimultaneously.nnThis causes a race condition issue where both threads can reach past thencheck that recv_id is not None before either of them set it to None. Ifnone of them set it to None before the other one tries to use it, annerror is raised.nnThis commit calls disable_recv before telling the actor to stop thenconnection. Since disable_recv is a blocking call, this ensures thatnrecv_id is being set to None before the actor thread begins to stop thenconnection.nnFixes #781n

backend: Change playback API (breaking change)While trying to remove traces of stop calls in core to get gapless working Infound we had no way to switch to switch tracks without triggering a play. Thisnchange fixes this by changing the backends playback provider API.nn- play() now _only_ starts playback and does not take any arguments.n- prepare_change() has been added, this could have been avoided with a kwarg ton  change_track(track), but that would break more backends.n- core has been updated to call prepare_change+change_track+play as needed.n- tests have been updated to handle this change.nnLonger term I hope to completely rework the playback API in backends, as 99% ofnour backends only use change_track(track) to translate URIs. So we should makensimple case simple, and handle mopidy-spotify / appsrc in some other way.n

core: Emit deprecation warningsThe warnings appear as warning level log messages if running Python onnthe mopidy/ directory like this:nnpython -W all mopidy -vnnor:nnpython -W all mopidy -o loglevels/py.warnings=warningnnWe don't suppress warnings when Pykka is the caller in general, but justnwhen Pykka is looking at all properties to create its actor proxies.nnWhen a deprecated property is used from another Pykka actor, only thenstack for the current actor thread is available for inspection, so thenwarning cannot show where the actual call site in the other actor threadnis. Though, if the warnings are made exceptions with:nnpython -W error mopidynnthen the stack traces will include the frames from all involved actornthreads, showing where the original call site is.n

backend: Change playback API (breaking change!)While trying to remove traces of stop calls in core to get gapless working Infound we had no way to switch to switch tracks without triggering a play. Thisnchange fixes this by changing the backends playback provider API.nn- play() now _only_ starts playback and does not take any arguments.n- prepare_change() has been added, this could have been avoided with a kwarg ton  change_track(track), but that would break more backends.n- core has been updated to call prepare_change+change_track+play as needed.n- tests have been updated to handle this change.nnLonger term I hope to completely rework the playback API in backends, as 99% ofnour backends only use change_track(track) to translate URIs. So we should makensimple case simple, and handle mopidy-spotify / appsrc in some other way.nnCherry picked from the WIP gapless branch.n

core: Make lookup(uris=...) return dict with all urisAll uris given to lookup should be in the result even if there is nonbackend to handle the uri, and the lookup result thus is an empty list.nnAs a side effect, future.get() is now called in the order of the URIsnin the `uris` list, making it easier to mock outnbackend.library.lookup() in core layer tests.n

core: Make sure the about-to-finish callback gets run in the actor.When about to finish gets called we are running in some GStreamer thread. Ournaudio code then calls the shim core callback which is responsible forntransferring our execution to the core actor thread and waiting for thenresponse. From this point we do normal actor calls to the backend(s) which innturn call into the audio actor. Since the initial audio code that was called isnoutside the actor this should never deadlock due to this loop.n

http: fix websocket broadcasts in Tornado 5.x (#1796)In Tornado 4.x and earlier, IOLoop.current() would return the global IOLooprnif there was no IOLoop already running in the calling thread. This was therncase when calling our websocket broadcast method from the HttpFrontend threadrnand so callbacks were correctly scheduled on the HttpServer thread's IOLoop.rnHowever, in Tornado 5.0+, the idea of a global IOLoop is gone and callingrnIOLoop.current() will simply create a new IOLoop if there isn't one alreadyrnrunning in the calling thread.rnThis incorrectly resulted in callbacks being scheduled on that new IOLooprnwhich is never actually started and so the broadcasts were never sent.rnrnThis is related to #1716.rn

This was therncase when calling our websocket broadcast method from the HttpFrontend threadrnand so callbacks were correctly scheduled on the HttpServer thread's IOLoop.rnHowever, in Tornado 5.0+, the idea of a global IOLoop is gone and callingrnIOLoop.current() will simply create a new IOLoop if there isn't one alreadyrnrunning in the calling thread.rnThis incorrectly resulted in callbacks being scheduled on that new IOLooprnwhich is never actually started and so the broadcasts were never sent.rnrnThis is related to #1716.rnn(cherry picked from commit 59a3935b7315ac9296b383f923fefbf4e33e5676)n

audio: Fix logging of GStreamer warning/errorOn Python 2, we used str(error) to get a native string representation,naka bytes, and then used .decode() on that to get a unicode string.nnOn Python 3, the str(error) call returns Unicode, which doesn't have an.decode() method, so the error/warning handler crashes.nnI added ipdb tracing, provoked an error, and investigated the objects wenget from GStreamer:nn- `error` is an GLib.GError which has a good str()/repr(), as well asn  .message, .domain, and .code attributes.n- `debug` is a stringnnThere were no traces of bytes that needed decoding in the objects.nnFixes #1851n
